Suppose \(S\) is a closed surface, \(\hat{\mathbf{n}}\) the outward unit normal,
\(V\) is the volume enclosed by \(S,\) and \(\mathbf{F}\) a vector field.

What best describes \(\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}\)?
$BR
%RADIORANDOM
It is a vector.
It is a number/scalar.
%CORRECT It is a scalar-valued function.
It is a vector field.
It is a constant.
It is positive.
It is yellow and sticky.
%END

What best describes
\(\displaystyle \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS\)?
$BR
%RADIORANDOM
It is a vector.
%CORRECT It is a number/scalar.
It is a scalar-valued function.
It is a vector field.
It is a constant.
It is positive.
It is green.
%END

The integral
\(\displaystyle \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS\) equals (by the divergence theorem)
$BR
%RADIORANDOM
\(\displaystyle \iint_S \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} \, dS\)
\(\displaystyle \iiint_S \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} \, dV\)
%CORRECT \(\displaystyle \iiint_V \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} \, dV\)
\(\displaystyle - \iiint_V \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} \, dV\)
\(\displaystyle \iiint_V \mathbf{F} \, dV\)
\((\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}) \operatorname{vol}(V)\)
\(-(\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}) \operatorname{vol}(V)\)
\((\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}) \operatorname{area}(S)\)
\(\operatorname{div}(\mathbf{F}) \operatorname{vol}(V)\)
%END

The integral
\(\displaystyle \iiint_V \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} \, dV\) equals
$BR
%RADIORANDOM
%CORRECT To know that we'd have to do the integration.
\((\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}) \operatorname{vol}(V)\)
0
42
%END

When, and really only when, can one say that
\(\displaystyle \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS\) equals
\((\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}) \operatorname{vol}(V)\)?
$BR
%RADIORANDOM
If \(V\) is small.
If \(\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}\) is small.
%CORRECT If \(\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}\) is a constant.
%END

So if \(\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} = 2\) at all points, can we say that
in this case \(\displaystyle \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS = 2 \operatorname{vol}(V)\)?
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT Yes.
No.
%END

And if \(\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} = 2x-z,\) can we say that
in this case \(\displaystyle \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS = (2x-z) \operatorname{vol}(V)\)?
$BR
%RADIO
Yes.
%CORRECT No.
%END

Is it true that for small \(V\) around a point \(p\) that
\(\displaystyle \frac{1}{\operatorname{vol}(V)} \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS\) equals
\(\nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}|_p\) (divergence at \(p\))?
$BR
%RADIORANDOM
%CORRECT Not necessarily.
Yes.
Yes, but only for very small \(V.\)
Yes, even for large \(V.\)
Yes on Sundays but not during the rest of the week.
%END

What can one say?
$BR
%RADIORANDOM
\(\displaystyle \frac{1}{\operatorname{vol}(V)} \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS = \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}|_p .\)
%CORRECT \(\displaystyle \frac{1}{\operatorname{vol}(V)} \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS \approx \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}|_p .\)
\(\displaystyle \frac{1}{\operatorname{vol}(V)} \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS = - \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}|_p .\)
\(\displaystyle \frac{1}{\operatorname{vol}(V)} \iint_S \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS = 0 .\)
%END
